          "body": "The 'Therefore, brethren' of 10:19 is the great pivot of the letter from indicative to imperative. Because of the blood (10:19) and the flesh (10:20) of Jesus, and because of the great priest over the house of God (10:21), three 'let us' commands follow. **Draw near** (10:22, *proserchōmetha*) — the verb of Levitical worship now applied to direct access through Christ, with cleansed conscience and sprinkled heart. **Hold fast the confession of our hope** (10:23) — public, articulated, unwavering, grounded in God's faithfulness. **Consider how to stimulate one another to love and good deeds** (10:24-25), which includes the negative command *not forsaking our own assembling together* (*episynagōgēn*). The three are inseparable: vertical access, verbal confession, horizontal stimulation. The audience is being tempted to disengage on all three axes — and the author refuses to let them disengage on any."
