          "title": "Apostasy, judgment, and the call to endurance (10:26-39)",
          "body": "The fourth and most severe warning of the letter follows immediately. *If we go on sinning willfully after receiving the knowledge of the truth, there no longer remains a sacrifice for sins* (10:26) — willful, settled, knowing repudiation of Christ leaves nothing else, because there is nothing else. The argument escalates by qal vakhomer (10:28-29): if rejecting Moses' law brought death without mercy on two or three witnesses, *how much severer punishment* for the one who has *trampled under foot the Son of God* and *insulted the Spirit of grace*? Verse 31 lands the warning: *it is a terrifying thing to fall into the hands of the living God*. But the warning yields to encouragement (10:32-34) — remember when you endured, when you accepted the seizure of property joyfully because you knew you had a better and lasting possession. Verses 35-39 close the chapter by launching chapter 11: *do not throw away your confidence*; *you have need of endurance*; *yet in a very little while He who is coming will come*; *My righteous one shall live by faith*. The chapter ends with the audience identified — *we are not of those who shrink back to destruction, but of those who have faith to the preserving of the soul*."
